06908nam a22009135i 9789048534982DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20182018ne     fo  d z      eng d  a2019667279  a97890485349827 a10.1515/97890485349822doi  a(DE-B1597)517388  a(OCoLC)1077769905  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL00aHQ1149.E85 7aHIS0100002bisacsh04aThe Youth of Early Modern Women /ced. by Margaret Louise Reeves, Elizabeth Storr Cohen. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2018  a1 online resource (328 p.) :b14 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aGendering the Late Medieval and Early Modern World00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tIntroduction -- tPart 1. Concepts and Representations -- t1. 'A Prospect of Flowers' -- t2. A Roving Woman -- t3. 'She is but a girl' -- t4. Flight and Confinement -- t5. Harlots and Camp Followers -- tPart 2. Self-Representations: Life-Writing and Letters -- t6. Three Sisters of Carmen -- t7. Elite English Girlhood in Early Modern Ireland -- t8. Young Women Negotiating Fashion in Early Modern Florence -- t9. 'Is it possible that my sister [...] has had a baby?' -- tPart 3. Training for Adulthood -- t10. Malleable Youth -- t11. The Material Culture of Female Youth in Bologna, 1550-1600 -- t12. Becoming a Woman in the Dutch Republic -- tPart 4. Courtship and Becoming Sexual -- t13. Straying and Led Astray -- t14. A Room of Their Own -- t15. In Search of a 'Remedy' -- tSupplementary Bibliography of Secondary Works -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aThrough fifteen essays that work from a rich array of primary sources, this collection makes the novel claim that early modern European women, like men, had a youth. European culture recognised that, between childhood and full adulthood, early modern women experienced distinctive physiological, social, and psychological transformations. Drawing on two mutually shaped layers of inquiry - cultural constructions of youth and lived experiences - these essays exploit a wide variety of sources, including literary and autobiographical works, conduct literature, judicial and asylum records, drawings, and material culture. The geographical and temporal ranges traverse England, Ireland, Italy, France, the Netherlands, Switzerland, Spain, and Mexico from the sixteenth to the eighteenth century. This volume brings fresh attention to representations of female youth, their own life writings, young women's training for adulthood, courtship, and the emergent sexual lives of young unmarried women.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0https://www.aup.nl/en/publish/open-access  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aYoung womenzEuropexHistory. 0aYoung womenzEuropexSocial conditions. 0aYouthzEuropexHistory. 4aEarly Modern Studies. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aSociology and Social History. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh  ayouth, women, early modern, girlhood, marriage.1 aAndersson, Christiane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Elizabeth S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Elizabeth Storr, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCouchman, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEckerle, Julie A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFranco, Alessandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHardwick, Julie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoller, Jacqueline, econtributor.4ct